00:00:34.030 --> 00:00:34.780
by using PR tools.

00:00:34.780 --> 00:00:38.160
So all of the tools
in it are PR tools.

00:00:38.160 --> 00:00:39.745
I thought I might
begin by trying

00:00:39.745 --> 00:00:42.250
to get us to agree on
what PR actually is.

00:00:42.250 --> 00:00:44.452
An awful lot of people think
PR is free advertising.

00:00:44.452 --> 00:00:45.160
YOu're in Google.

00:00:45.160 --> 00:00:46.784
You know advertising
isn't free, right?

00:00:46.784 --> 00:00:48.720
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:48.720 --> 00:00:51.190
Advertising, you buy the
space, you put something in it.

00:00:51.190 --> 00:00:53.356
And the purpose of advertising
is to sell a product.

00:00:53.356 --> 00:00:55.240
So it works or it
doesn't work on the basis

00:00:55.240 --> 00:00:57.400
of how much rpduct did shift?

00:00:57.400 --> 00:00:59.170
It's very easy to analyze.

00:00:59.170 --> 00:01:02.500
Public Relations, on the
other hand, creates stories.

00:01:02.500 --> 00:01:04.680
It tells you who people
are and what they do

00:01:04.680 --> 00:01:06.680
and why they're passionate
about their business,

00:01:06.680 --> 00:01:08.471
and why you should
actually invest in them.

00:01:08.471 --> 00:01:12.245
I often think public relations
people are like doctors.

00:01:12.245 --> 00:01:13.703
Because they work
from a goody bag.

00:01:13.703 --> 00:01:15.578
but the goody bag has
loads of tools in them.

00:01:15.578 --> 00:01:18.370
So if you go to a doctor
and you have a cough,

00:01:18.370 --> 00:01:20.662
the doctor may say to you,
meh, it's a bit of a cough.

00:01:20.662 --> 00:01:21.370
It's no big deal.

00:01:21.370 --> 00:01:22.981
You need a cough bottle.

00:01:22.981 --> 00:01:24.502
The doctor may
equally look at you

00:01:24.502 --> 00:01:26.877
and say, oh, I don't like the
sound of that cough at all.

00:01:26.877 --> 00:01:29.077
OK, I need you get x-rays.

00:01:29.077 --> 00:01:31.160
Last time I heard somebody
with a cough like that,

00:01:31.160 --> 00:01:32.451
I never saw them a second time.

00:01:32.451 --> 00:01:34.600
Or the doctor may well
lookat you and say,

00:01:34.600 --> 00:01:34.970
you're a malingerer.

00:01:34.970 --> 00:01:36.040
There's nothing wrong with you.

00:01:36.040 --> 00:01:36.700
Go back to work.

00:01:36.700 --> 00:01:38.075
I'm not giving
you a certificate.

00:01:38.075 --> 00:01:40.033
But he dips into a
goody bag of tools

00:01:40.033 --> 00:01:41.560
and say, here's what you need.

00:01:41.560 --> 00:01:43.680
PR people do exactly
the same thing.

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:45.237
We look at a business
and we say, OK,

00:01:45.237 --> 00:01:47.070
if you're trying to
communicate with people,

00:01:47.070 --> 00:01:48.942
which tool do you need to use?

00:01:48.942 --> 00:01:50.400
So should you be
using exhibitions?

00:01:50.400 --> 00:01:52.015
Should you be using e-zines?

00:01:52.015 --> 00:01:53.540
Should you be
using social media?

00:01:53.540 --> 00:01:56.710
Should you be
using sponsorships?

00:01:56.710 --> 00:01:58.744
What's the tool
that will work best

00:01:58.744 --> 00:01:59.910
for each different audience?

00:01:59.910 --> 00:02:03.020
Because you won't reach
everybody with the same tool.

00:02:03.020 --> 00:02:05.300
So this book is
about 10 of the tools

00:02:05.300 --> 00:02:09.699
that I believe are most
relevant to people in SMEs.

00:02:09.699 --> 00:02:12.850
Before I move onto them, I
should mention the word spin.

00:02:12.850 --> 00:02:15.330
Because every time you hear
the word public relations,

00:02:15.330 --> 00:02:16.190
you hear spin.

00:02:16.190 --> 00:02:20.170
And PR people have this huge
thing about, we do not spin.

00:02:20.170 --> 00:02:21.350
We are not spin doctors.

00:02:21.350 --> 00:02:23.710
We are in public relations.

00:02:23.710 --> 00:02:27.160
I was introduced about
three or four years ago

00:02:27.160 --> 00:02:30.600
as the princess of
the dark art of spin.

00:02:30.600 --> 00:02:31.760
I absolutely adored it.

00:02:31.760 --> 00:02:34.460
I have dined out
on it ever since.

00:02:34.460 --> 00:02:36.920
Because I think that
is exactly what we do.

00:02:36.920 --> 00:02:39.100
Businesses do it, people do it.

00:02:39.100 --> 00:02:40.320
I wore a suit this morning.

00:02:40.320 --> 00:02:42.115
I'm serious about
being an author.

00:02:42.115 --> 00:02:43.025
That's my spin.

00:02:43.025 --> 00:02:44.710
I could've come in
in a pair of jeans.

00:02:44.710 --> 00:02:47.245
You would've had an entirely
different visual spin.

00:02:47.245 --> 00:02:49.620
You chose to dress exactly
the way you chose this morning

00:02:49.620 --> 00:02:52.140
because it says something
about you, the mood you're in,

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:55.330
what you want to project to
people in the world today.

00:02:55.330 --> 00:02:55.960
That's spin.

00:02:55.960 --> 00:02:57.530
That's a visual spin.

00:02:57.530 --> 00:02:59.072
We also do it by text.

00:02:59.072 --> 00:03:00.530
So there are two
ways you can spin.

00:03:00.530 --> 00:03:01.540
One is visually.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:03.620
What you look like
says something.

00:03:03.620 --> 00:03:05.380
It creates an expectation.

00:03:05.380 --> 00:03:07.280
But equally, text
does the same thing.

00:03:07.280 --> 00:03:08.405
Let me give you an example.

00:03:08.405 --> 00:03:15.630
If I said that my best
friend is a drug addict,

00:03:15.630 --> 00:03:17.490
what immediately
comes into your head?

00:03:17.490 --> 00:03:19.904
What does drug addict say?

00:03:19.904 --> 00:03:21.257
AUDIENCE: Pills.

00:03:21.257 --> 00:03:22.340
AUDIENCE: She takes drugs.

00:03:22.340 --> 00:03:23.548
AUDIENCE: Hypodermic needles?

00:03:23.548 --> 00:03:26.645
ELLEN GUNNING:
Pills, Takes drugs.

00:03:26.645 --> 00:03:28.200
A bit down and out.

00:03:28.200 --> 00:03:33.300
Not really the best, probably
in a bad place right now.

00:03:33.300 --> 00:03:35.440
Needs to feed a
habit, so God only

00:03:35.440 --> 00:03:37.930
knows how they actually get
enough money to feed the habit.

00:03:37.930 --> 00:03:40.760
The whole "drug addict," just
the use of the words "drug

00:03:40.760 --> 00:03:45.110
addict" says, mm, I wouldn't
have thought she associated

00:03:45.110 --> 00:03:46.812
with those kinds of people.

00:03:46.812 --> 00:03:49.790
If, on the other hand,
I said, my best friend

00:03:49.790 --> 00:03:54.150
is a recreational user, you'd
go whoa, too many parties.

00:03:54.150 --> 00:03:55.510
Too much white stuff.

00:03:55.510 --> 00:03:56.760
Got to cut back on that stuff.

00:03:56.760 --> 00:03:57.880
It'll kill you eventually.

00:03:57.880 --> 00:04:00.060
It's a whole different spin.

00:04:00.060 --> 00:04:02.690
You're still talking about
somebody who uses drugs.

00:04:02.690 --> 00:04:03.430
But it's a spin.

00:04:03.430 --> 00:04:04.910
It's a textual spin.

00:04:04.910 --> 00:04:06.710
Your head creates a
different picture.

00:04:06.710 --> 00:04:07.930
And that's what PR people do.

00:04:07.930 --> 00:04:09.350
They say, don't look over there.

00:04:09.350 --> 00:04:10.537
Look over here.

00:04:10.537 --> 00:04:11.620
That's what spin is about.

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:12.890
It's not about telling a lie.

00:04:12.890 --> 00:04:15.513
It's about diverting your
attention just a little bit.

00:04:15.513 --> 00:04:20.390
So visual spin, let me look at
four of the 10 Red Hot Tips,

00:04:20.390 --> 00:04:22.660
possibly, that are
included in this.

00:04:22.660 --> 00:04:26.085
Visual, photo calls, we
live in a visual era.

00:04:26.085 --> 00:04:29.270
Look at the way we watch
news, and the way news

00:04:29.270 --> 00:04:30.920
is presented to us,
how it's changed

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:32.860
in the last 10 or 15 years.

00:04:32.860 --> 00:04:34.647
If you looked at
news years ago, it

00:04:34.647 --> 00:04:36.980
was one person sitting to a
camera on television saying,

00:04:36.980 --> 00:04:38.957
here is the news, and
you had a clip behind.

00:04:38.957 --> 00:04:41.077
If you watch news
on television now,

00:04:41.077 --> 00:04:42.660
you've got all these
boxes coming down

00:04:42.660 --> 00:04:44.950
the side with short little
breaking pieces of news.

00:04:44.950 --> 00:04:47.190
You've got ticker tape
running underneath.

00:04:47.190 --> 00:04:50.240
Nobody actually sits there
and waits for the next story.

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:51.500
We have no patience.

00:04:51.500 --> 00:04:53.275
But the visual
tells us something.

00:04:53.275 --> 00:04:57.801
It's like this morning, there
was an avalanche in Italy.

00:04:57.801 --> 00:04:58.800
I've seen the avalanche.

00:04:58.800 --> 00:05:00.120
I know what ahppened.

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:01.850
It's a visual kind of thing.

00:05:01.850 --> 00:05:05.860
If you can create a really good
visual, people will remember.

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:08.150
They associate it
with your business.

00:05:08.150 --> 00:05:10.520
There are two ways to do
it. one is by photo call,

00:05:10.520 --> 00:05:11.630
and one is by photo shoot.

00:05:11.630 --> 00:05:13.690
Photo call is where you
actually invite all of the media

00:05:13.690 --> 00:05:14.250
to attend.

00:05:14.250 --> 00:05:16.080
And you set up the
picture for them.

00:05:16.080 --> 00:05:18.457
Photo shoot is where you
create the photograph,

00:05:18.457 --> 00:05:19.665
and you send it to the media.

00:05:19.665 --> 00:05:22.180
So let me give you
example of both.

00:05:22.180 --> 00:05:25.370
I must warn you in advance,
small, little people,

00:05:25.370 --> 00:05:27.630
vertically challenged,
generally called children,

00:05:27.630 --> 00:05:28.330
I don't have any of them.

00:05:28.330 --> 00:05:30.413
I find it very difficult
to communicate with them.

00:05:30.413 --> 00:05:31.180
OK?

00:05:31.180 --> 00:05:32.847
We need to contextualize
this story, OK?

00:05:32.847 --> 00:05:34.804
So I have a guy that was
vertically challenged.

00:05:34.804 --> 00:05:36.725
Until they're my height
and make eye contact

00:05:36.725 --> 00:05:38.930
and speak in fully-formed
sentences they're like,

00:05:38.930 --> 00:05:40.290
nice to meet you kid, move on.

00:05:40.290 --> 00:05:41.170
OK?

00:05:41.170 --> 00:05:43.284
So I'm doing this
photo call and it's

00:05:43.284 --> 00:05:44.450
for the opening of a school.

00:05:44.450 --> 00:05:45.560
It's a day school.

00:05:45.560 --> 00:05:48.200
And I have two children, a
photographer sitting beside me.

00:05:48.200 --> 00:05:51.090
And he says, OK, what I want to
get is that traditional shot.

00:05:51.090 --> 00:05:53.366
I want to get a little boy,
little girl holding hands,

00:05:53.366 --> 00:05:54.490
walking to school, day one.

00:05:54.490 --> 00:05:55.580
I thought, easy.

00:05:55.580 --> 00:05:57.236
I told you, I have no kids.

00:05:57.236 --> 00:05:57.735
OK?

00:05:57.735 --> 00:05:58.921
So I was scrambling.

00:05:58.921 --> 00:05:59.420
Two?

00:05:59.420 --> 00:05:59.690
There's a little boy.

00:05:59.690 --> 00:06:00.940
There, that little girl there.

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:02.095
So yeah, they look nice.

00:06:02.095 --> 00:06:04.220
Sean, do me a favor and
hold Maureen's hand please.

00:06:04.220 --> 00:06:05.980
(ALTERED VOICE) No.

00:06:05.980 --> 00:06:08.101
I'm not doing it.

00:06:08.101 --> 00:06:09.055
Right.

00:06:09.055 --> 00:06:10.970
Maureen, hold
Sean's hand please.

00:06:10.970 --> 00:06:13.140
(ALTERED VOICE) Oh, OK.

00:06:13.140 --> 00:06:14.220
And she puts her hand in.

00:06:14.220 --> 00:06:16.800
And he goes, (ALTERED
VOICE) I'm not doing it.

00:06:16.800 --> 00:06:20.120
Able Well, we go through this
about two or three times.

00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:23.120
I said to the photographer, this
kid has an attitude problem.

00:06:23.120 --> 00:06:25.084
He's not going to hold her hand.

00:06:25.084 --> 00:06:27.860
And he said, no, and we're
not going to get the shot.

00:06:27.860 --> 00:06:29.330
I said, no, no,
we'll get the shot.

00:06:29.330 --> 00:06:30.650
I just need to lose the child.

00:06:30.650 --> 00:06:31.430
OK?

00:06:31.430 --> 00:06:33.096
So without even
thinking, I turn around.

00:06:33.096 --> 00:06:34.262
Now, I'm in the zone.

00:06:34.262 --> 00:06:36.470
So I turned around and said,
who owns the little boy?

00:06:36.470 --> 00:06:39.180
And the photographer turns
back to me and went, who owns?

00:06:39.180 --> 00:06:42.048
Who owns the little boy?

00:06:42.048 --> 00:06:43.010
I'm dead.

00:06:43.010 --> 00:06:44.540
I'm going to record
this on film.

00:06:44.540 --> 00:06:46.216
Somebody is going to kill you.

00:06:46.216 --> 00:06:48.010
You do not own a child.

00:06:48.010 --> 00:06:51.290
And this father came thundering
over the group, like a lunatic.

00:06:51.290 --> 00:06:53.192
And he goes, I'm Sean's father.

00:06:53.192 --> 00:06:55.290
And I still haven't
really registered

00:06:55.290 --> 00:06:56.760
what the photographer said.

00:06:56.760 --> 00:06:59.040
So I said, great.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:00.070
Do me a favor, will you?

00:07:00.070 --> 00:07:01.540
The photographer's trying to get
a shot for "The Irish Times."

00:07:01.540 --> 00:07:02.020
The kid won't cooperate.

00:07:02.020 --> 00:07:03.340
I just want him
to hold her hand.

00:07:03.340 --> 00:07:03.990
He won't do it.

00:07:03.990 --> 00:07:05.990
Sorry, but that
kid has his chance.

00:07:05.990 --> 00:07:06.570
He's gone.

00:07:06.570 --> 00:07:09.590
I need to put another little
boy in, in place of him.

00:07:09.590 --> 00:07:10.870
I don't do tactful, either.

00:07:10.870 --> 00:07:12.370
I should have mentioned.

00:07:12.370 --> 00:07:15.590
What was the father's reaction?

00:07:15.590 --> 00:07:17.407
Any idea?

00:07:17.407 --> 00:07:18.543
AUDIENCE: Defensive?

00:07:18.543 --> 00:07:20.209
AUDIENCE: He made the
kid hold her hand.

00:07:20.209 --> 00:07:23.011
ELLEN GUNNING: Told the
child to hold hands?

00:07:23.011 --> 00:07:24.260
He had the child sideways.

00:07:24.260 --> 00:07:25.320
He goes, Sean!

00:07:25.320 --> 00:07:27.110
You hold her hand
right-by-God now!

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:29.640
Because all the father
heard was "Irish Times."

00:07:29.640 --> 00:07:31.600
He didn't hear the child's
being uncooperative.

00:07:31.600 --> 00:07:33.359
He didn't hear who
owns the child?

00:07:33.359 --> 00:07:34.900
He heard "Irish
Times," and my child.

00:07:34.900 --> 00:07:36.170
And we got the front
page of "The Irish Times"

00:07:36.170 --> 00:07:37.740
the next day, with the child.

00:07:37.740 --> 00:07:39.201
The little girl going, eh.

00:07:39.201 --> 00:07:41.149
And the little boy, rawr!

00:07:41.149 --> 00:07:42.520
But it was a classic shot.

00:07:42.520 --> 00:07:45.170
If you'd pinch the child, you
couldn't have set it up better.

00:07:45.170 --> 00:07:48.259
[LAUGHTER]

00:07:48.259 --> 00:07:50.050
YOu're learning a lot
about the way I work.

00:07:50.050 --> 00:07:51.980
Probably more than
you needed to know.

00:07:51.980 --> 00:07:54.391
From the school's point of
view, what they wanted was,

00:07:54.391 --> 00:07:56.390
they were looking for a
bit of publicity to say,

00:07:56.390 --> 00:07:57.410
the school has opened.

00:07:57.410 --> 00:07:58.310
It's a new school.

00:07:58.310 --> 00:07:59.340
It's in this area.

00:07:59.340 --> 00:08:01.700
And they ended up was front
page of the "Irish Times,"

00:08:01.700 --> 00:08:04.130
with a shot that said, this
is the new school that opened.

00:08:04.130 --> 00:08:05.420
And it was outside of Dublin.

00:08:05.420 --> 00:08:07.795
So the chances of actually
getting that kind of publicity

00:08:07.795 --> 00:08:08.330
were unreal.

00:08:08.330 --> 00:08:09.680
But it was a great photograph.

00:08:09.680 --> 00:08:12.560
So if you take a great shot,
people will look at it.

00:08:12.560 --> 00:08:14.010
And they remember it.

00:08:14.010 --> 00:08:17.280
The exmple that I used in the
book was from Butler's Pantry.

00:08:17.280 --> 00:08:19.540
You all familiar
with Butler's Pantry?

00:08:19.540 --> 00:08:23.330
Butler's Pantry, probably
the best way to describe it,

00:08:23.330 --> 00:08:25.170
it's like a gourmet food outlet.

00:08:25.170 --> 00:08:26.670
You're probably in
there if you want

00:08:26.670 --> 00:08:29.330
to buy really good quality,
fresh, homemade food

00:08:29.330 --> 00:08:30.805
on your way home in the evening.

00:08:30.805 --> 00:08:31.950
They're kind of
like, do you know

00:08:31.950 --> 00:08:33.741
the way Marks &amp; Spencers
do those food ads?

00:08:33.741 --> 00:08:36.590
You know the way you could've
completely eaten an entire meal

00:08:36.590 --> 00:08:38.700
and you're stuffed and thinking,
I never want to see food again?

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:40.925
And a Marks &amp; Spencers food
ad comes on and you go,

00:08:40.925 --> 00:08:41.950
that looks lovely.

00:08:41.950 --> 00:08:43.520
Then suddenly
you're hungry again.

00:08:43.520 --> 00:08:45.350
Food, if you're going
to promote food,

00:08:45.350 --> 00:08:48.540
you have promote food
with that yumminess.

00:08:48.540 --> 00:08:51.157
And Butler's Pantry bring in
a professional photographer

00:08:51.157 --> 00:08:52.490
each time they take photographs.

00:08:52.490 --> 00:08:55.250
But because photography
is so expensive,

00:08:55.250 --> 00:08:58.550
and it's probably only
about half the price that it

00:08:58.550 --> 00:09:00.120
was five or six years ago.

00:09:00.120 --> 00:09:03.100
Five or six years
ago, before the crash,

00:09:03.100 --> 00:09:05.810
if you brought in a photograph
to do any photo shoot,

00:09:05.810 --> 00:09:08.780
you said to the client,
you need 1,200 to 1,500.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:09.665
You won't get out.

00:09:09.665 --> 00:09:11.040
You won't get
change out of that.

00:09:11.040 --> 00:09:13.081
Now we're looking at
somewhere around 300 to 600.

00:09:13.081 --> 00:09:14.410
So it's a big change.

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:16.280
But for a small
business, you're still

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:18.240
looking at bringing
in a photograph

00:09:18.240 --> 00:09:19.115
to take a photograph.

00:09:19.115 --> 00:09:20.840
And I dont' know if
anybody will use it.

00:09:20.840 --> 00:09:22.908
So I have a really
good-quality photograph,

00:09:22.908 --> 00:09:24.075
but will it be used?

00:09:24.075 --> 00:09:27.110
And what Butler's Pantry do is
they trial all the photographs.

00:09:27.110 --> 00:09:30.580
So if they're doing a new,
I don't know, salmon dish,

00:09:30.580 --> 00:09:32.440
they storyboard
the entire thing.

00:09:32.440 --> 00:09:35.055
So this is how we would
like to promote salmon.

00:09:35.055 --> 00:09:37.330
This is what we want
people to think and feel.

00:09:37.330 --> 00:09:39.380
When we say salmon, we
people to go, oh, salmon.

00:09:39.380 --> 00:09:41.570
I haven't had salmon
in a long time.

00:09:41.570 --> 00:09:43.850
Fresh fish,
gorgeous, [INAUDIBLE]

00:09:43.850 --> 00:09:45.399
of knowledge, whatever it is.

00:09:45.399 --> 00:09:47.190
And then they try to
create the photograph.

00:09:47.190 --> 00:09:50.130
So they spend days
seeing what works best?

00:09:50.130 --> 00:09:51.290
Should I put this here?

00:09:51.290 --> 00:09:53.000
Should I put that there?

00:09:53.000 --> 00:09:55.035
How, exactly, do
we mix the people?

00:09:55.035 --> 00:09:55.910
The groups together.

00:09:55.910 --> 00:09:58.250
And when they think they
have it exactly right,

00:09:58.250 --> 00:10:00.290
then they get the
photographer in.

00:10:00.290 --> 00:10:02.470
And the photographer
literally shoots it.

00:10:02.470 --> 00:10:04.650
But the photographs
that they take

00:10:04.650 --> 00:10:07.970
have been used for up
to five years, which

00:10:07.970 --> 00:10:10.130
is a very long time
to get out of a photo.

00:10:10.130 --> 00:10:11.874
But it's good value.

00:10:11.874 --> 00:10:14.330
But their attitude is, if
they spend that much money,

00:10:14.330 --> 00:10:16.704
they really want to be sure
before the photographer comes

00:10:16.704 --> 00:10:19.464
in the door that it's giving the
message that they want it to.

00:10:19.464 --> 00:10:20.630
And that's a visual message.

00:10:20.630 --> 00:10:21.796
And that's public relations.

00:10:21.796 --> 00:10:23.300
That's a photo call.

00:10:23.300 --> 00:10:25.596
The second area I wanted
to look at was sponsorship.

00:10:25.596 --> 00:10:27.470
Because people seem to
think that sponsorship

00:10:27.470 --> 00:10:30.380
is all about having
lots of money.

00:10:30.380 --> 00:10:32.120
Everybody knows
the big sponsorhips

00:10:32.120 --> 00:10:33.350
because they're in your face.

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:35.930
They've got huge
budgets behind them.

00:10:35.930 --> 00:10:37.887
Sponsorship can work
really, really well

00:10:37.887 --> 00:10:39.470
for a small-to-medium-size
enterprise.

00:10:39.470 --> 00:10:42.560
But it only works really
well if, like everything else

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:44.845
you do in life, you
put time into it

00:10:44.845 --> 00:10:45.940
and you think it through.

00:10:45.940 --> 00:10:48.110
So let me give you two
examples of sponsorship,

00:10:48.110 --> 00:10:49.024
one good and one bad.

00:10:49.024 --> 00:10:50.440
The example I used
in the book was

00:10:50.440 --> 00:10:53.630
a company called Action Coach.

00:10:53.630 --> 00:10:55.730
Action Coach worked with
small-to-medium-size

00:10:55.730 --> 00:10:56.990
enterprises.

00:10:56.990 --> 00:11:00.830
And their job is that they
basically go into companies

00:11:00.830 --> 00:11:02.960
and they teach them how
to be more competitive.

00:11:02.960 --> 00:11:07.280
So that may be how to take
risks in certain markets.

00:11:07.280 --> 00:11:10.520
Or they may say to them,
look, your targeted market

00:11:10.520 --> 00:11:11.370
is far too broad.

00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:12.105
You're never going
to reach everybody.

00:11:12.105 --> 00:11:13.647
You need to try a
little bit tighter.

00:11:13.647 --> 00:11:15.688
Or it may be that you just
don't know what you're

00:11:15.688 --> 00:11:16.800
doing, in terms of money.

00:11:16.800 --> 00:11:18.928
So we need to actually
teach you a little bit more

00:11:18.928 --> 00:11:21.190
about profit and loss,
and how to manage money

00:11:21.190 --> 00:11:22.806
and how to look after cash flow.

00:11:22.806 --> 00:11:24.680
And basically, they work
with small business,

00:11:24.680 --> 00:11:26.897
trying to get them
to the next step.

00:11:26.897 --> 00:11:27.980
They're based in Ballymun.

00:11:27.980 --> 00:11:30.350
And they're very passionate
about being in Ballymun,

00:11:30.350 --> 00:11:32.870
and what can they do
for people in Ballymun?

00:11:32.870 --> 00:11:34.320
And I'm going to be shot at.

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:35.690
There's a rugby player--

00:11:35.690 --> 00:11:37.370
I'm hopeless on sports--

00:11:37.370 --> 00:11:38.820
who's from Ballymun.

00:11:38.820 --> 00:11:41.000
Does anybody know who
I'm talking about?

00:11:41.000 --> 00:11:42.725
Anyway, or he could
be a golf player.

00:11:42.725 --> 00:11:43.950
Anyway, there's a guy who's
a very well-known sports

00:11:43.950 --> 00:11:45.530
person from Ballymun.

00:11:45.530 --> 00:11:47.400
And they met him
at a talk one day.

00:11:47.400 --> 00:11:49.010
Literally, they were just
sitting, listening to him talk.

00:11:49.010 --> 00:11:50.175
And he was talking
about the fact

00:11:50.175 --> 00:11:51.410
that he'd come from Ballymun.

00:11:51.410 --> 00:11:52.630
His family were very poor.

00:11:52.630 --> 00:11:54.560
He'd done very well.

00:11:54.560 --> 00:11:57.170
He was looking to give
something back to the area.

00:11:57.170 --> 00:11:58.640
It started them thinking.

00:11:58.640 --> 00:12:00.360
They developed a board game.

00:12:00.360 --> 00:12:03.950
The board game teaches you how
to deal with profit and loss,

00:12:03.950 --> 00:12:06.010
how to look after cash
flow, how to take risks,

00:12:06.010 --> 00:12:07.445
how to analyze risks.

00:12:07.445 --> 00:12:09.103
And they decided
what they would do,

00:12:09.103 --> 00:12:10.686
is they would work
with local schools.

00:12:10.686 --> 00:12:12.680
And they would go
into local schools

00:12:12.680 --> 00:12:15.290
and create a competition,
but teach children

00:12:15.290 --> 00:12:17.490
how to build up these skills.

00:12:17.490 --> 00:12:19.357
And they objective was twofold.

00:12:19.357 --> 00:12:21.440
One was that they might
actually find that they've

00:12:21.440 --> 00:12:24.300
an iotnerest in commerce
or becoming enterepreneurs,

00:12:24.300 --> 00:12:26.750
or owning their own
business. but the second

00:12:26.750 --> 00:12:28.878
was that if they
never did, they'd

00:12:28.878 --> 00:12:31.044
have developed skills which
were useful for the rest

00:12:31.044 --> 00:12:32.470
of their lives.

00:12:32.470 --> 00:12:35.210
And that's a really good
example of sponsorship.

00:12:35.210 --> 00:12:38.053
Another example, by
comparison, you're

00:12:38.053 --> 00:12:40.236
in what we all call
Googleland now.

00:12:40.236 --> 00:12:42.717
But I used to live around
the corner, on Ringsend road.

00:12:42.717 --> 00:12:44.800
So I don't know whether
you should be welcoming me

00:12:44.800 --> 00:12:46.570
to Googleland or I should be
thanking you for inviting me

00:12:46.570 --> 00:12:47.320
back home again.

00:12:47.320 --> 00:12:49.002
But I've lived on Ringsend Road.

00:12:49.002 --> 00:12:51.210
And I was very involved in
the community in Ringsend.

00:12:51.210 --> 00:12:53.410
Because I lived
there all my life.

00:12:53.410 --> 00:12:55.000
I got married, moved
away, came back

00:12:55.000 --> 00:12:57.131
to live there when
I was married.

00:12:57.131 --> 00:12:58.630
I only moved out
about 15 years ago.

00:12:58.630 --> 00:13:01.310
And I just love being
involved in community.

00:13:01.310 --> 00:13:02.847
Because I think
it's who we all are.

00:13:02.847 --> 00:13:05.180
We don't have enough community
involvement, whether it's

00:13:05.180 --> 00:13:07.013
community of interest,
or physical community

00:13:07.013 --> 00:13:07.750
in which we live.

00:13:07.750 --> 00:13:10.240
We had a Glamourous
Granny competition

00:13:10.240 --> 00:13:12.221
quite a few years ago.

00:13:12.221 --> 00:13:13.720
And the Glamorous
Granny competition

00:13:13.720 --> 00:13:16.365
was sponsored by the
local beauticians, which I

00:13:16.365 --> 00:13:18.246
thought was a really nice fit.

00:13:18.246 --> 00:13:19.218
It was clever.

00:13:19.218 --> 00:13:20.880
The Glamourous
Grannies all came in.

00:13:20.880 --> 00:13:22.530
And they ranged in age.

00:13:22.530 --> 00:13:24.760
At that time, I've gone
back probably 20 years,

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:26.560
from 55 to 75.

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:30.760
Now they range in
age from 35 to 75.

00:13:30.760 --> 00:13:32.650
But they ranged in age
from about 55 to 75.

00:13:32.650 --> 00:13:34.230
So most of the ladies came in.

00:13:34.230 --> 00:13:36.446
And they had that
lovely gray, buffed hair

00:13:36.446 --> 00:13:38.570
that looked like they'd
just taken the curlers out.

00:13:38.570 --> 00:13:40.300
You know that look
that people have?

00:13:40.300 --> 00:13:40.800
Who

00:13:40.800 --> 00:13:42.650
And they came up and they sang.

00:13:42.650 --> 00:13:45.190
They talked about their
three children and their two

00:13:45.190 --> 00:13:47.950
grandchildren, and how old they
were and what their names were.

00:13:47.950 --> 00:13:50.500
Very nice, very
pleasant evening.

00:13:50.500 --> 00:13:52.690
All of the husbands, by
the way, who were alive,

00:13:52.690 --> 00:13:53.440
came in and stood.

00:13:53.440 --> 00:13:55.515
Only came in for
"her" bit, and came in

00:13:55.515 --> 00:13:57.076
and stood at the
end of the hall,

00:13:57.076 --> 00:13:59.200
watch her, and went that's
fine, and went back off,

00:13:59.200 --> 00:14:00.659
out for a pint
again, and wouldn't

00:14:00.659 --> 00:14:01.950
stay for the rest of the night.

00:14:01.950 --> 00:14:03.300
But they did their bit.

00:14:03.300 --> 00:14:04.590
They did it really well.

00:14:04.590 --> 00:14:08.440
And the beauticians was ggiving
the prize for whatever it was.

00:14:08.440 --> 00:14:11.910
200 euros worth of goods
in the beauticians.

00:14:11.910 --> 00:14:14.822
They sent in a young model
to present the pirze.

00:14:14.822 --> 00:14:16.530
So you've got a roomful
of people who are

00:14:16.530 --> 00:14:18.810
55, 75 years age, all female.

00:14:18.810 --> 00:14:22.240
And they send in this
absolutely drop-dead

00:14:22.240 --> 00:14:23.345
gorgeous-looking girl.

00:14:23.345 --> 00:14:24.460
She was tall.

00:14:24.460 --> 00:14:25.870
She was stick-insect thin.

00:14:25.870 --> 00:14:27.520
She was on heels
this high, like she

00:14:27.520 --> 00:14:29.230
was teetering on Jimmy Choos.

00:14:29.230 --> 00:14:30.730
She walked the way models do.

00:14:30.730 --> 00:14:32.724
They kind of walk like
cats on high heels.

00:14:32.724 --> 00:14:35.452
And she strutted her stuff
all the way up the stage.

00:14:35.452 --> 00:14:36.680
She looked amazing.

00:14:36.680 --> 00:14:38.680
She came up and she
presented all of the prizes.

00:14:38.680 --> 00:14:42.800
And what everybody did in the
audience, as she walked past,

00:14:42.800 --> 00:14:46.240
was say, oh my god, look at
the height of those heels.

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:48.220
Can you remember ever
wearing heels that high?

00:14:48.220 --> 00:14:50.280
Oh yeah, but it was before
I had my first child.

00:14:50.280 --> 00:14:51.850
Never wore heels
that high since.

00:14:51.850 --> 00:14:54.280
Look at her little waist.

00:14:54.280 --> 00:14:55.460
She's a size 8.

00:14:55.460 --> 00:14:57.406
It'd say she's a size 10.

00:14:57.406 --> 00:14:57.905
[GASPS]

00:14:57.905 --> 00:14:59.356
I was never a size 10.

00:14:59.356 --> 00:15:00.730
The smallest I
ever was was a 12.

00:15:00.730 --> 00:15:03.910
And actually what they did
was they reminded people

00:15:03.910 --> 00:15:05.930
of what it was like
to be young or single,

00:15:05.930 --> 00:15:07.340
or before they had children.

00:15:07.340 --> 00:15:09.610
They brought them
back to their 20s.

00:15:09.610 --> 00:15:12.745
They did not target them
as 55-to-75-year-olds.

00:15:12.745 --> 00:15:14.651
What they should have
done, in my opinion,

00:15:14.651 --> 00:15:16.650
was they should have got
somebody who was either

00:15:16.650 --> 00:15:18.149
very well-known in
the community who

00:15:18.149 --> 00:15:20.770
was of that age, or the
previous winner, the last year,

00:15:20.770 --> 00:15:23.020
and brought her in
and pampered her.

00:15:23.020 --> 00:15:26.620
So that somebody in their 60s
or 70s preseneted the prize.

00:15:26.620 --> 00:15:28.780
And instead of saying,
look at her little waist,

00:15:28.780 --> 00:15:30.380
and do you remember
those high heels?

00:15:30.380 --> 00:15:33.310
You would actually say, my
god, look at the change in her?

00:15:33.310 --> 00:15:34.771
Doesn't she look amazing?

00:15:34.771 --> 00:15:37.990
Actually, this is what the
beauticians did because it then

00:15:37.990 --> 00:15:40.570
reminds people, it makes
the association with people.

00:15:40.570 --> 00:15:44.140
And that, to my idea, would
have been a good sponsorship.

00:15:44.140 --> 00:15:45.099
They actually misfired.

00:15:45.099 --> 00:15:46.889
They sponsored, they
put the money into it.

00:15:46.889 --> 00:15:48.930
They sent somebody in
to present the prizes.

00:15:48.930 --> 00:15:51.232
I doubt that anybody
even connected the two.

00:15:51.232 --> 00:15:52.190
It's not about selling.

00:15:52.190 --> 00:15:54.106
But I doubt that anybody
walked past and said,

00:15:54.106 --> 00:15:56.170
that's the beauticians
that sponsored.

00:15:56.170 --> 00:15:57.940
Because they didn't
make that connection.

00:15:57.940 --> 00:16:00.496
So sponsorship,
very little money.

00:16:00.496 --> 00:16:01.870
The other thing
with sponsorship,

00:16:01.870 --> 00:16:05.423
just as I think of it, when
we moved back into Ringsend,

00:16:05.423 --> 00:16:08.410
we moved back after
oh, I don't know.

00:16:08.410 --> 00:16:10.640
I'd grown up and lived
there till I was about 18.

00:16:10.640 --> 00:16:13.907
And I moved back about
oh, probably 25 years ago.

00:16:13.907 --> 00:16:15.490
And when I moved
back, they were still

00:16:15.490 --> 00:16:17.300
delivering milk to the door.

00:16:17.300 --> 00:16:18.850
But I'm what everybody
calls a yuppy.

00:16:18.850 --> 00:16:19.996
So I'm gone early
morning in the morning

00:16:19.996 --> 00:16:21.190
and I'm back late
in the evening.

00:16:21.190 --> 00:16:22.795
Ilove the way Ringsenders always
have their own pronunciations

00:16:22.795 --> 00:16:23.420
and everything.

00:16:23.420 --> 00:16:25.129
Dubliners do it
as a general rule.

00:16:25.129 --> 00:16:26.420
So I was gone early in the day.

00:16:26.420 --> 00:16:27.460
And literally, it
got to the stage

00:16:27.460 --> 00:16:28.710
where you'd come outside
the door in the morning

00:16:28.710 --> 00:16:30.654
and go, oh, for God's
sake, there's no milk.

00:16:30.654 --> 00:16:33.530
Or you come out and go, yippe
ki-yay, we have milk today.

00:16:33.530 --> 00:16:34.680
And it drove me insane.

00:16:34.680 --> 00:16:36.430
So at one stage I met with
one of the neighbors and said,

00:16:36.430 --> 00:16:37.520
well, do me a favor.

00:16:37.520 --> 00:16:39.580
If you see the milkman,
find out what I owe him.

00:16:39.580 --> 00:16:40.177
Pay him off.

00:16:40.177 --> 00:16:41.260
Tell him thanks very much.

00:16:41.260 --> 00:16:44.610
I'm going to just get
the milk as I need it.

00:16:44.610 --> 00:16:45.516
And she said, really?

00:16:45.516 --> 00:16:47.156
What'd the milkman do on you?

00:16:47.156 --> 00:16:49.130
What's the problem
with the milkman?

00:16:49.130 --> 00:16:51.130
And I said, there's no
problem with the milkman.

00:16:51.130 --> 00:16:52.840
It's just that the
milk is there some days

00:16:52.840 --> 00:16:53.830
and it's not there other days.

00:16:53.830 --> 00:16:55.450
And she said, oh I
see, Ms. Gunning.

00:16:55.450 --> 00:16:56.516
Oh yeah, yeah.

00:16:56.516 --> 00:16:57.890
We're not all like
you, you know.

00:16:57.890 --> 00:16:59.534
We don't all leave in the
middle of the night, come back

00:16:59.534 --> 00:17:00.659
in the middle of the night.

00:17:00.659 --> 00:17:02.448
That poor man gets
up at four o'clock

00:17:02.448 --> 00:17:03.906
in the morning to
deliver the milk.

00:17:03.906 --> 00:17:04.339
I said, I know.

00:17:04.339 --> 00:17:05.839
But he should be
getting up at 3:30.

00:17:05.839 --> 00:17:08.110
Free Because I don't get
the milk outside the door.

00:17:08.110 --> 00:17:09.654
She said, I'll tell
you what I'll do.

00:17:09.654 --> 00:17:11.154
When I'm passing
by, if there's milk

00:17:11.154 --> 00:17:12.981
outside your door in
the morning, I'll take

00:17:12.981 --> 00:17:14.230
and I'll put it into the shop.

00:17:14.230 --> 00:17:15.650
And I'll keep it cold for you.

00:17:15.650 --> 00:17:17.025
And you can collect it from
the shop in the evning.

00:17:17.025 --> 00:17:18.250
I said, just think about this.

00:17:18.250 --> 00:17:19.083
This is not logical.

00:17:19.083 --> 00:17:21.473
He jumps outof the van,
leaves me the milk.

00:17:21.473 --> 00:17:22.931
You come by and go
oh look, there's

00:17:22.931 --> 00:17:24.390
the milk-- because I've already
left-- and brings it down

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:25.480
to the shop.

00:17:25.480 --> 00:17:26.380
It's just crazy.

00:17:26.380 --> 00:17:28.900
Just pay the guy off and
tell me how much I owe.

00:17:28.900 --> 00:17:30.385
And she said, no, no, no.

00:17:30.385 --> 00:17:31.600
You don't understand.

00:17:31.600 --> 00:17:33.740
This man goes out of his way.

00:17:33.740 --> 00:17:37.320
He's been delivering milk in
this area for years and years.

00:17:37.320 --> 00:17:40.450
And he goes out of his way
to sponsor the local soccer

00:17:40.450 --> 00:17:41.619
club every year.

00:17:41.619 --> 00:17:43.285
He buys them a whole
section of jerseys.

00:17:43.285 --> 00:17:46.365
I thought it was a brilliant
example of somebody who

00:17:46.365 --> 00:17:47.859
had connected to the community.

00:17:47.859 --> 00:17:48.650
I wasn't connected.

00:17:48.650 --> 00:17:49.520
I didn't have kids.

00:17:49.520 --> 00:17:51.790
I didn't respectwhat
this man was doing.

00:17:51.790 --> 00:17:53.792
What she did and the
whole community did,

00:17:53.792 --> 00:17:54.970
and that's why we
buy our milk fromhim.

00:17:54.970 --> 00:17:56.210
The man has to earn a living.

00:17:56.210 --> 00:17:57.001
And he's very good.

00:17:57.001 --> 00:17:58.940
And he doesn't have
to buy these T-shirts.

00:17:58.940 --> 00:18:01.195
And it really brought
it home that sponsorship

00:18:01.195 --> 00:18:05.020
had such a long-term impact
on people around you.

00:18:05.020 --> 00:18:07.129
That man was getting
business because people

00:18:07.129 --> 00:18:09.420
who were grandparents or
people like me who had no kids

00:18:09.420 --> 00:18:11.442
were told, he's
earning his lving.

00:18:11.442 --> 00:18:13.050
He's contributing
to the community.

00:18:13.050 --> 00:18:14.160
So good sponsorships.

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:17.170
Well, I don't know what it
cost him for a set of jerseys

00:18:17.170 --> 00:18:18.004
for a football team.

00:18:18.004 --> 00:18:19.545
But it wasn't a huge
amount of money.

00:18:19.545 --> 00:18:22.380
But he got the return out of it
year on year, on year on year.

00:18:22.380 --> 00:18:24.840
So sponsorship, second one.

00:18:24.840 --> 00:18:26.090
Third one is exhibitions.

00:18:26.090 --> 00:18:28.680
The number of people who
don't use exhibitions

00:18:28.680 --> 00:18:31.706
properly-- exhibitions,
you're going to pay to attend.

00:18:31.706 --> 00:18:33.550
So you've decided as
a business that this

00:18:33.550 --> 00:18:35.140
is where you should be.

00:18:35.140 --> 00:18:38.430
But the number of businesses
who don't then follow through--

00:18:38.430 --> 00:18:41.425
if you book an exhibition and
you book it early, if you know

00:18:41.425 --> 00:18:44.137
in January that you're doing
an exhibition in September,

00:18:44.137 --> 00:18:46.720
what happens is that people send
you out all of these notices.

00:18:46.720 --> 00:18:48.964
The exhibition organizers
send you notices and say,

00:18:48.964 --> 00:18:51.380
so will you be doing anything
different at the exhibition?

00:18:51.380 --> 00:18:53.046
Are you launching
anything extraoridnry?

00:18:53.046 --> 00:18:54.670
Do you have any unusual guests?

00:18:54.670 --> 00:18:57.130
is there anything you want to
tell us about your stall that

00:18:57.130 --> 00:18:58.605
makes it different?

00:18:58.605 --> 00:18:59.980
Small-to-medium-size
enterprises,

00:18:59.980 --> 00:19:02.321
because they're busy, look
at it and go, for God's sake,

00:19:02.321 --> 00:19:04.820
how do I know in Januaray what
I'm going to do in September?

00:19:04.820 --> 00:19:05.725
So they leave it.

00:19:05.725 --> 00:19:08.100
They just throw it to one side
and say, I'll do it later.

00:19:08.100 --> 00:19:11.260
And then come August, they
fill in all the information.

00:19:11.260 --> 00:19:13.120
And whoever was
organizing has already

00:19:13.120 --> 00:19:15.340
decided who gets the publicity.

00:19:15.340 --> 00:19:18.410
Because in January or February,
the organizer is saying,

00:19:18.410 --> 00:19:20.740
I need to know where my
stories are coming from.

00:19:20.740 --> 00:19:22.780
So if you take the
trouble to tell me

00:19:22.780 --> 00:19:25.970
that you're doing something
different, I'll promote you.

00:19:25.970 --> 00:19:28.440
So it's free PR that's sitting
there, waiting for them.

00:19:28.440 --> 00:19:30.065
But people don't
actually take the time

00:19:30.065 --> 00:19:32.610
to do it because they need
to move so much earlier.

00:19:32.610 --> 00:19:34.110
And really, if they
did, they'd have

00:19:34.110 --> 00:19:36.910
a whole team of professional
people promoting them.

00:19:36.910 --> 00:19:37.660
It's a no-brainer.

00:19:37.660 --> 00:19:39.010
It should make sense.

00:19:39.010 --> 00:19:42.660
I was on an exhibition
for TY students, students

00:19:42.660 --> 00:19:46.245
and teachers, last year, just
before the book came out.

00:19:46.245 --> 00:19:49.581
And there was a company called
High Rock Productions, who had

00:19:49.581 --> 00:19:50.830
taken an exhibition stand out.

00:19:50.830 --> 00:19:52.450
And the exhibition was huge.

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:55.730
It was in this massive
warehouse in Carlow somewhere.

00:19:55.730 --> 00:19:57.530
We came into the warehouse.

00:19:57.530 --> 00:19:59.260
And every single
stand has something

00:19:59.260 --> 00:20:00.730
for transitionary students.

00:20:00.730 --> 00:20:04.570
So you had, "Learn to
Climb the [INAUDIBLE],,

00:20:04.570 --> 00:20:07.230
we'll teach you how to
make presentation skills,

00:20:07.230 --> 00:20:10.670
come kayaking with us--

00:20:10.670 --> 00:20:13.230
whole loads of it-- we
teach you first aid.

00:20:13.230 --> 00:20:15.719
A mix between the
skills that you

00:20:15.719 --> 00:20:17.260
would use as an
individual and things

00:20:17.260 --> 00:20:19.809
that you went out
and did as groups.

00:20:19.809 --> 00:20:21.850
And this particular group,
High Rock Productions,

00:20:21.850 --> 00:20:24.577
I stopped because when
I came round the corner,

00:20:24.577 --> 00:20:26.160
there was an entire
square closed off.

00:20:26.160 --> 00:20:28.810
Now, what they actually
do is they go into schools

00:20:28.810 --> 00:20:31.330
and they help
children speak Irish.

00:20:31.330 --> 00:20:33.970
So they prep them for
their oral Irish exams.

00:20:33.970 --> 00:20:36.075
But they do it by
creating this play.

00:20:36.075 --> 00:20:37.094
So it's very creative.

00:20:37.094 --> 00:20:38.260
They work with the children.

00:20:38.260 --> 00:20:39.140
They create this play.

00:20:39.140 --> 00:20:40.970
And when they've made this
play, they help to put it on.

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:41.960
It's all true Irish.

00:20:41.960 --> 00:20:45.260
So they become more confident
about speaking the language.

00:20:45.260 --> 00:20:48.689
Very hard thing to promote
to children, most of whom

00:20:48.689 --> 00:20:51.170
probably haven't an interest
in and oral Irish and "exams,"

00:20:51.170 --> 00:20:52.710
and they're looking at
TY, which is the year

00:20:52.710 --> 00:20:53.790
in between their exams.

00:20:53.790 --> 00:20:55.430
So they're not focusing on it.

00:20:55.430 --> 00:20:57.814
And what this group had done
was they had taken a square.

00:20:57.814 --> 00:20:59.730
They had about three
times the amount of space

00:20:59.730 --> 00:21:00.813
that they should have had.

00:21:00.813 --> 00:21:02.910
So they'd taken a square
in from of the stand.

00:21:02.910 --> 00:21:03.868
And they closed it off.

00:21:03.868 --> 00:21:05.710
And they were playing
virtual tennis.

00:21:05.710 --> 00:21:07.247
It was absolutely brilliant.

00:21:07.247 --> 00:21:09.580
Because one of the guys was
tehre and he was saying, OK,

00:21:09.580 --> 00:21:10.163
are you ready?

00:21:10.163 --> 00:21:12.560
Serve-- step off
the court, please.

00:21:12.560 --> 00:21:13.480
You're on the court.

00:21:13.480 --> 00:21:14.230
Get off the court.

00:21:14.230 --> 00:21:16.510
And as people walked
past, they went, here?

00:21:16.510 --> 00:21:17.120
Oh, sorry.

00:21:17.120 --> 00:21:17.690
Sorry.

00:21:17.690 --> 00:21:18.202
Am I OK?

00:21:18.202 --> 00:21:18.910
Back, back, back.

00:21:18.910 --> 00:21:20.355
And everybody got it.

00:21:20.355 --> 00:21:21.350
There was nothing.

00:21:21.350 --> 00:21:22.630
There was absolutely nothing.

00:21:22.630 --> 00:21:24.296
But everybody go it
and they stood back.

00:21:24.296 --> 00:21:27.040
And when the ball went out of
play, they would say, sorry,

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:27.740
could I have the ball there?

00:21:27.740 --> 00:21:28.250
Yeah.

00:21:28.250 --> 00:21:29.660
No, no, at your other foot.

00:21:29.660 --> 00:21:30.160
There?

00:21:30.160 --> 00:21:30.460
Yeah.

00:21:30.460 --> 00:21:30.760
Can you throw it?

00:21:30.760 --> 00:21:31.400
Thank you.

00:21:31.400 --> 00:21:32.584
Yeah, got it.

00:21:32.584 --> 00:21:34.210
And everybody stopped to watch.

00:21:34.210 --> 00:21:35.380
It was brilliant.

00:21:35.380 --> 00:21:38.410
It took a huge amount of
attention to their side.

00:21:38.410 --> 00:21:41.188
And they gave everybody
leaflets about what they did.

00:21:41.188 --> 00:21:44.650
I thought it was
really, really clever.

00:21:44.650 --> 00:21:46.210
When I interviewed
them afterwards,

00:21:46.210 --> 00:21:47.980
I said, by the way,
brilliant idea.

00:21:47.980 --> 00:21:50.022
You took over so
much space, lads.

00:21:50.022 --> 00:21:50.521
Smart.

00:21:50.521 --> 00:21:53.062
And they said, yeah,
but I'm not sure it was

00:21:53.062 --> 00:21:54.270
as smart as it could've been.

00:21:54.270 --> 00:21:56.750
Because it targeted
all of the children.

00:21:56.750 --> 00:21:59.500
And their query was that
the exhibition was targeted

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:01.510
to both children and teachers.

00:22:01.510 --> 00:22:03.150
And with hindsight,
they weren't sure

00:22:03.150 --> 00:22:05.285
if you could target
both in one exhibition.

00:22:05.285 --> 00:22:07.645
And what they had done
was they had successfully

00:22:07.645 --> 00:22:10.053
got all of the children involed.

00:22:10.053 --> 00:22:13.060
But the children didn't decide
what they would do in TY year.

00:22:13.060 --> 00:22:14.440
The teachers did.

00:22:14.440 --> 00:22:15.970
So they'd actually misfired.

00:22:15.970 --> 00:22:17.231
They got loads of attention.

00:22:17.231 --> 00:22:18.980
They got loads of kids
talking about them.

00:22:18.980 --> 00:22:22.500
But they didn't have the teacher
saying, what a good idea.

00:22:22.500 --> 00:22:25.230
And people didn't
connect virtual tennis

00:22:25.230 --> 00:22:27.656
with what they were
actually doing.

00:22:27.656 --> 00:22:29.870
So it was interesting,
because to my eyes, coming in

00:22:29.870 --> 00:22:32.480
as an outsider, I
thought, very smart.

00:22:32.480 --> 00:22:34.480
You've captured the whole room.

00:22:34.480 --> 00:22:37.270
When they analyzed it
aftweard they thought,

00:22:37.270 --> 00:22:39.740
good btu not as brilliant
as it could've been.

00:22:39.740 --> 00:22:42.860
I suppose one of the things that
I'm really conscious of the PR

00:22:42.860 --> 00:22:46.120
is that it's not rocket science.

00:22:46.120 --> 00:22:47.570
It does take a lot of time.

00:22:47.570 --> 00:22:50.030
But most of the skills
can be easily learned.

00:22:50.030 --> 00:22:52.705
But it's about not
doing things on the fly.

00:22:52.705 --> 00:22:54.429
Because PR doesn't
respond well to things

00:22:54.429 --> 00:22:55.470
that are done on the fly.

00:22:55.470 --> 00:22:57.095
You end up saying
why didn't that work?

00:22:57.095 --> 00:22:59.081
I've put loads of time
into it on short notice.

00:22:59.081 --> 00:23:00.830
It works really well
if you sit down early

00:23:00.830 --> 00:23:02.830
and say, who am I
trying to reach?

00:23:02.830 --> 00:23:04.340
What am I trying to acheive?

00:23:04.340 --> 00:23:05.250
How do I get them?

00:23:05.250 --> 00:23:07.172
What are they interested in?

00:23:07.172 --> 00:23:11.322
One of the very clever companies
that I profiled in the book

00:23:11.322 --> 00:23:13.914
was Newbridge Silver.

00:23:13.914 --> 00:23:15.830
I'm a big believer in
third-party endorsement.

00:23:15.830 --> 00:23:18.534
If you stand up and say I
run a wonderful business.

00:23:18.534 --> 00:23:20.025
That's a marvelous business.

00:23:20.025 --> 00:23:21.650
Everybody here just
loves what they do.

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:24.100
We provide great quality
product, or whwatever.

00:23:24.100 --> 00:23:26.775
Everybody would say, well, you
would say that, wouldn't you?

00:23:26.775 --> 00:23:28.900
Which is fair enough,
because you're not going say,

00:23:28.900 --> 00:23:30.032
I run a rubbish business.

00:23:30.032 --> 00:23:31.240
Who was the guy who did that?

00:23:31.240 --> 00:23:33.090
His junior business went bust.

00:23:33.090 --> 00:23:35.300
There was a man who famously
said he just produces

00:23:35.300 --> 00:23:36.780
junk jewelry and people buy it.

00:23:36.780 --> 00:23:39.732
And the entire business went
bust very shortly afterwards.

00:23:39.732 --> 00:23:41.982
Because everybody said, well,
I buy that junk jewelry.

00:23:41.982 --> 00:23:43.220
And he thinks it's junk?

00:23:43.220 --> 00:23:45.250
Why do I waste my
time buying it.

00:23:45.250 --> 00:23:47.090
But as a general
rule, you're looking

00:23:47.090 --> 00:23:50.300
at third-party endorsement is
where somebody says of you,

00:23:50.300 --> 00:23:51.320
it's good.

00:23:51.320 --> 00:23:53.240
Or where you create
an association.

00:23:53.240 --> 00:23:55.750
And Newbridge are very clever
at creating the association.

00:23:55.750 --> 00:23:58.800
They came up with this
idea of style ambassadors.

00:23:58.800 --> 00:24:01.550
So instead of it
just being jewelry,

00:24:01.550 --> 00:24:04.580
they started using
people like Amy Huberman

00:24:04.580 --> 00:24:08.730
and Naomi Campbell and
Ronan O'Gara, and saying,

00:24:08.730 --> 00:24:12.725
OK, these are people who you
can associate with our jewelry.

00:24:12.725 --> 00:24:14.945
Interestingly enough,
they used Linda Gray.

00:24:14.945 --> 00:24:17.078
You know the lady from "Dallas?"

00:24:17.078 --> 00:24:18.050
That's interesting.

00:24:18.050 --> 00:24:21.510
How many people actually know
Linda Gray from "Dallas?"

00:24:21.510 --> 00:24:22.020
Very few.

00:24:22.020 --> 00:24:22.520
Excellent.

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:23.170
Thank you.

00:24:23.170 --> 00:24:24.087
It makes my point.

00:24:24.087 --> 00:24:26.420
Because she was introduced
on "The Late Late" years ago,

00:24:26.420 --> 00:24:28.830
when they started using her
And she was wearing big,

00:24:28.830 --> 00:24:29.910
chunky Newbridge jewelry.

00:24:29.910 --> 00:24:30.410
Now,

00:24:30.410 --> 00:24:32.147
Now, she's a fabulous woman.

00:24:32.147 --> 00:24:33.730
She was about in her
70's at the time.

00:24:33.730 --> 00:24:35.619
You would've given her
like, 52 at the most.

00:24:35.619 --> 00:24:36.410
She looked amazing.

00:24:36.410 --> 00:24:38.460
And she was wearing
this chunky jewelry.

00:24:38.460 --> 00:24:40.940
And you looked and
thought, she actually

00:24:40.940 --> 00:24:43.046
isn't the type of person
who wears chunky jewelry.

00:24:43.046 --> 00:24:46.865
If she had been doing Newbridge
Cutlery, dining at home,

00:24:46.865 --> 00:24:49.990
and here's how the
posh dine, it probably

00:24:49.990 --> 00:24:51.800
would've sat much more easily.

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:53.774
But doing chukny
jewelry at her age,

00:24:53.774 --> 00:24:55.940
even though she was glamourous,
didn't seem to work.

00:24:55.940 --> 00:24:58.830
But it did work very well
with the likes of Amy Huberman

00:24:58.830 --> 00:25:00.140
and Naomi Campbell.

00:25:00.140 --> 00:25:03.102
And what they do is they
associate the people

00:25:03.102 --> 00:25:03.810
with the product.

00:25:03.810 --> 00:25:06.890
So if they're stylish and
tehy wear our product,

00:25:06.890 --> 00:25:08.094
you should do the same.

00:25:08.094 --> 00:25:10.635
Very interestingly, when I spoke
to the lady who coordinates,

00:25:10.635 --> 00:25:13.292
their brand ambassadors,
I said to them,

00:25:13.292 --> 00:25:14.390
it must be very difficult.

00:25:14.390 --> 00:25:18.770
Because I innocently assumed
that if you were Amy Huberman

00:25:18.770 --> 00:25:21.352
and you were wearing Newbridge,
that as Newbridge you

00:25:21.352 --> 00:25:22.727
would say, by the
way, sweet pea,

00:25:22.727 --> 00:25:24.727
I do not want you wearing
anybody else's jewelry

00:25:24.727 --> 00:25:26.890
because we're paying
you shedloads of money.

00:25:26.890 --> 00:25:28.770
So I expect to see
you in Newbridge only.

00:25:28.770 --> 00:25:30.400
And she said, oh God, no.

00:25:30.400 --> 00:25:31.350
No, no, no.

00:25:31.350 --> 00:25:34.730
Because nobody who follows Amy
Huberman will believe that.

00:25:34.730 --> 00:25:37.070
They would know that of
course she has her own style

00:25:37.070 --> 00:25:39.320
and she wears any one of a
number of different things.

00:25:39.320 --> 00:25:41.480
So when she chooses
to wear Newbridge,

00:25:41.480 --> 00:25:43.010
we're happy that she does so.

00:25:43.010 --> 00:25:44.890
But when she chooses
to wear somebody else,

00:25:44.890 --> 00:25:45.770
we're equally happy.

00:25:45.770 --> 00:25:47.540
And I thought it
was very clever.

00:25:47.540 --> 00:25:49.120
Because it then
doesn't look like we

00:25:49.120 --> 00:25:50.930
pay you to wear this
jewelry all the time.

00:25:50.930 --> 00:25:52.300
It looks like yes, you're
a brand ambassador,

00:25:52.300 --> 00:25:54.000
but when you feel
like wearing it.

00:25:54.000 --> 00:25:56.094
And she actually
wore a long chain.

00:25:56.094 --> 00:25:58.552
When she announced that she
was expecting her second child,

00:25:58.552 --> 00:26:00.050
she wore a long Newbridge chain.

00:26:00.050 --> 00:26:02.340
And she tweeted because
she's a mad tweeter.

00:26:02.340 --> 00:26:05.050
And she tweeted
something about the coat.

00:26:05.050 --> 00:26:05.810
I can't remember.

00:26:05.810 --> 00:26:09.140
"Bump by BOD, chain
by Newbridge."

00:26:09.140 --> 00:26:09.990
And they sold out.

00:26:09.990 --> 00:26:11.825
They had no idea she
was going to do it.

00:26:11.825 --> 00:26:14.070
They knew when she was
doing the photo, apparently,

00:26:14.070 --> 00:26:15.040
that she was pregnant.

00:26:15.040 --> 00:26:16.494
But she didn't want to
say anything about it.

00:26:16.494 --> 00:26:17.650
And when she
eventually tweeted it,

00:26:17.650 --> 00:26:18.941
it was just like it's her call.

00:26:18.941 --> 00:26:19.820
It's her baby.

00:26:19.820 --> 00:26:20.750
So she tweeted it.

00:26:20.750 --> 00:26:22.040
They weren't expecting it.

00:26:22.040 --> 00:26:23.354
They sold out of the chain.

00:26:23.354 --> 00:26:24.770
They went into a
second production

00:26:24.770 --> 00:26:26.377
and sold out of the
second production

00:26:26.377 --> 00:26:28.400
as well, the number
of people who

00:26:28.400 --> 00:26:30.500
just wanted to buy that chain.

00:26:30.500 --> 00:26:32.330
So the association from
their point of view

00:26:32.330 --> 00:26:33.380
worked really well.

00:26:33.380 --> 00:26:35.830
They associated with people
that people want to look like,

00:26:35.830 --> 00:26:37.310
or people want to emulate.

00:26:37.310 --> 00:26:40.699
And they followed that through
with the Museum of Style Icons.

00:26:40.699 --> 00:26:42.740
So they actually have all
of these clothes, which

00:26:42.740 --> 00:26:44.656
are actually, if you've
been down to see them,

00:26:44.656 --> 00:26:47.270
the clothes are moth
eaten and it's incredible,

00:26:47.270 --> 00:26:48.530
how old the clothes are.

00:26:48.530 --> 00:26:50.210
But they were Audrey Hepburn's.

00:26:50.210 --> 00:26:52.470
Or they were--
who's the lady who

00:26:52.470 --> 00:26:55.010
went to become Princess
Grace of Monacco?

00:26:55.010 --> 00:26:55.760
Grace Kelly.

00:26:55.760 --> 00:26:58.460
So you end up looking at these
clothes thinking, wow, that's

00:26:58.460 --> 00:26:59.180
what people acutally wore.

00:26:59.180 --> 00:27:01.471
Did anybody go down for the
Michael Jackson exhibition,

00:27:01.471 --> 00:27:02.405
by the way?

00:27:02.405 --> 00:27:05.270
They had Michael
Jackson's clothes.

00:27:05.270 --> 00:27:07.385
You know the famous
glove, the sparkly glove?

00:27:07.385 --> 00:27:08.060
They had it.

00:27:08.060 --> 00:27:09.440
I just decided I had to go down.

00:27:09.440 --> 00:27:10.650
You never saw anything
like the trousers.

