00:30:57.040 --> 00:31:00.550
about your audience and
considering who exactly

00:31:00.550 --> 00:31:01.700
am I trying to reach?

00:31:01.700 --> 00:31:05.863
So other than just asking
yourself those really specific

00:31:05.863 --> 00:31:09.610
questions, what else can
we be asking ourselves?

00:31:09.610 --> 00:31:12.240
Or how else can we really
answer that question?

00:31:12.240 --> 00:31:15.540
ELLEN GUNNING: I think the
trap most people fall into,

00:31:15.540 --> 00:31:18.210
we all look to reach people
using the same methods

00:31:18.210 --> 00:31:19.230
that we used.

00:31:19.230 --> 00:31:20.879
So if I read "The
Irish Times," I

00:31:20.879 --> 00:31:22.420
assume that everybody
I want to reach

00:31:22.420 --> 00:31:23.046
will read "The Irish Times."

00:31:23.046 --> 00:31:25.060
If I live on social
media, I assume they all

00:31:25.060 --> 00:31:26.590
live on social media.

00:31:26.590 --> 00:31:29.584
What happens is we forget
to look at the other side.

00:31:29.584 --> 00:31:30.750
I call it where people feed.

00:31:30.750 --> 00:31:33.780
I atteneded a conference
a few years back.

00:31:33.780 --> 00:31:35.682
And the guy talked
about chasing pigeons.

00:31:35.682 --> 00:31:37.640
I don't know if you've
heard this story before.

00:31:37.640 --> 00:31:38.348
It was brilliant.

00:31:38.348 --> 00:31:40.325
And he talked about
if you chase pigeons.

00:31:40.325 --> 00:31:43.000
If you try to feed pigeons
and you chase them in a park,

00:31:43.000 --> 00:31:44.150
the pigeons fly away.

00:31:44.150 --> 00:31:44.754
Like, go away.

00:31:44.754 --> 00:31:45.420
Stop chasing me.

00:31:45.420 --> 00:31:46.420
You're bothering me.

00:31:46.420 --> 00:31:48.666
Watch the old man who
sits down on the park seat

00:31:48.666 --> 00:31:50.082
and he just keeps
dropping crumbs.

00:31:50.082 --> 00:31:51.966
And the pigeons come to him.

00:31:51.966 --> 00:31:54.340
And it's about knowing, what
are the pigeons looking for?

00:31:54.340 --> 00:31:54.610
Bread.

00:31:54.610 --> 00:31:55.550
They're not looking for hassle.

00:31:55.550 --> 00:31:56.390
They'll come to you.

00:31:56.390 --> 00:31:58.931
And the more often they come to
you, the more they trust you.

00:31:58.931 --> 00:32:01.290
And they more you build
up their confidence.

00:32:01.290 --> 00:32:04.110
With any kind of an
audience, your problem

00:32:04.110 --> 00:32:06.235
is that you look at them
from the inside out.

00:32:06.235 --> 00:32:08.100
You should look
from the outside in.

00:32:08.100 --> 00:32:09.840
The chances are,
with any business,

00:32:09.840 --> 00:32:10.980
you actually need to use--

00:32:10.980 --> 00:32:15.274
they said originally, when radio
was overtaken by television

00:32:15.274 --> 00:32:16.815
or when television
was invented, they

00:32:16.815 --> 00:32:18.020
said it was the death of radio.

00:32:18.020 --> 00:32:19.464
When newspapers
gave in, they said

00:32:19.464 --> 00:32:20.880
it was the death
of something else.

00:32:20.880 --> 00:32:23.046
When socieal media came in,
they said, oh that's it.

00:32:23.046 --> 00:32:24.780
People will only
use social media.

00:32:24.780 --> 00:32:26.100
It's actually not true.

00:32:26.100 --> 00:32:27.950
We did an interview
at the weekend.

00:32:27.950 --> 00:32:30.688
We're teaching a TV
presenters course.

