So ask her about Meryl
Streep's speech, Donald Trump

00:32:50.010 --> 00:32:53.600
retweeting, the Golden Globes,
all that kind of stuff.

00:32:53.600 --> 00:32:56.090
It was fascinating to watch.

00:32:56.090 --> 00:32:57.389
So Meryl Streep's speech--

00:32:57.389 --> 00:32:59.680
you are all familiar that
Marilyn Streep made a speech?

00:32:59.680 --> 00:33:02.307
OK, just checking.

00:33:02.307 --> 00:33:04.640
Meryl Streep's speech at the
Golden Globes, what did you

00:33:04.640 --> 00:33:05.163
think of it.

00:33:05.163 --> 00:33:06.412
And she said oh, I don't know.

00:33:06.412 --> 00:33:07.120
I didn't hear it.

00:33:07.120 --> 00:33:08.614
What was it about?

00:33:08.614 --> 00:33:09.599
And she OK.

00:33:09.599 --> 00:33:11.390
And she gave her a very
quick explanaation.

00:33:11.390 --> 00:33:12.930
And she said, uh--

00:33:12.930 --> 00:33:14.720
and Donald Trump
retweeted, you know,

00:33:14.720 --> 00:33:16.928
"the most overrated actress
in America," or whatever.

00:33:16.928 --> 00:33:18.654
And she said, yeah,
I didn't see that.

00:33:18.654 --> 00:33:21.560
And she said, OK, well, what
do you think about the fact

00:33:21.560 --> 00:33:25.516
that the President-elect is
tweeting about an actress?

00:33:25.516 --> 00:33:26.940
And she said, I don't know.

00:33:26.940 --> 00:33:28.190
I haven't seen any of it.

00:33:28.190 --> 00:33:29.000
I have no idea.

00:33:29.000 --> 00:33:32.936
I catch up on all my social
media on Sunday mornings.

00:33:32.936 --> 00:33:34.580
And it was eye-opening.

00:33:34.580 --> 00:33:36.710
It was like,
everybody in the room

00:33:36.710 --> 00:33:39.430
assumed everybody had
heard Meryl Streep.

00:33:39.430 --> 00:33:40.690
How could you miss it?

00:33:40.690 --> 00:33:43.110
Because it had been tackled
from so many different angles.

00:33:43.110 --> 00:33:45.813
And in her world,
Sunday morning was when

00:33:45.813 --> 00:33:47.035
she caught up on everything.

00:33:47.035 --> 00:33:49.410
So it's looking at your audience
from their point of view

00:33:49.410 --> 00:33:51.840
and saying, if they're
Sunday newspaper readers,

00:33:51.840 --> 00:33:53.465
then that's where
you need to get them.

00:33:53.465 --> 00:33:55.798
It doesn't matter that you
can be all over social media.

00:33:55.798 --> 00:33:56.646
They don't find you.

00:33:56.646 --> 00:33:58.520
It's they're social
media people, then where?

00:33:58.520 --> 00:34:00.360
What bloggers do
they actually read?

00:34:00.360 --> 00:34:01.460
Who influences them?

00:34:01.460 --> 00:34:02.799
Who do they think is rubbish?

00:34:02.799 --> 00:34:04.090
Who do they think is brilliant?

00:34:04.090 --> 00:34:07.360
If it's radio, which radio
stations do they listen to?

00:34:07.360 --> 00:34:09.789
So are they "Newtalk"
listeners or RTE 1 listeners?

00:34:09.789 --> 00:34:11.570
It's a different listener.

00:34:11.570 --> 00:34:13.976
You tune to the dial and
you stay, more or less,

00:34:13.976 --> 00:34:15.850
on the dial if you're
of a certain age group.

00:34:15.850 --> 00:34:18.320
And then if you're of a
certain age group as well,

00:34:18.320 --> 00:34:20.260
do you actually go
hunting for information?

00:34:20.260 --> 00:34:22.830
Or does it come
into you by email?

00:34:22.830 --> 00:34:25.111
So it's really breaking
down your audience,

00:34:25.111 --> 00:34:26.694
and probably choosing
a different tune

00:34:26.694 --> 00:34:28.100
for ech subsection.

