00:39:14.674 --> 00:39:16.090
ELLEN GUNNING: I'm
sure he didn't.

00:39:16.090 --> 00:39:19.300
AUDIENCE: So my question
is if an SME at this size

00:39:19.300 --> 00:39:23.140
is to do a PR investment,
what kind of advice

00:39:23.140 --> 00:39:26.019
can you give defining
what success is?

00:39:26.019 --> 00:39:28.060
ELLEN GUNNING: It depends
on what you're actually

00:39:28.060 --> 00:39:29.950
trying to achieve.

00:39:29.950 --> 00:39:34.030
So, what sponsorship is best
at is creating name awareness.

00:39:34.030 --> 00:39:36.040
If you look at any of
the great sponsorships

00:39:36.040 --> 00:39:38.414
they started because people
were moving into new markets,

00:39:38.414 --> 00:39:39.931
or they had changed their name.

00:39:39.931 --> 00:39:41.930
So the company was no
longer known as one thing.

00:39:41.930 --> 00:39:43.910
It was now known
as something else.

00:39:43.910 --> 00:39:47.990
When-- who sponsored the first
cycle race around Ireland?

00:39:47.990 --> 00:39:49.680
Was it Toyota?

00:39:49.680 --> 00:39:51.939
And they sponsored it
because it's a car company.

00:39:51.939 --> 00:39:53.480
Doesn't make sense
that a car company

00:39:53.480 --> 00:39:54.563
would sponsor cycle races.

00:39:54.563 --> 00:39:57.387
It was at the time when Stephen
Roche and all of those guys

00:39:57.387 --> 00:39:58.220
were winning medals.

00:39:58.220 --> 00:40:00.600
But it was because Toyota
used to be called--

00:40:00.600 --> 00:40:03.085
was it Toyota who used
to be called Datsun?

00:40:03.085 --> 00:40:04.460
And people didn't
know the brand.

00:40:04.460 --> 00:40:06.365
So the whole idea
was, if you create

00:40:06.365 --> 00:40:08.740
an awareness of the brand,
people say, I've heard of you.

00:40:08.740 --> 00:40:10.270
And what's the story?

00:40:10.270 --> 00:40:11.450
It opens the door a bit.

00:40:11.450 --> 00:40:14.420
So what sponsorship is best at
is creating brand awareness.

00:40:14.420 --> 00:40:16.140
So if you're an SME,
and you're trying

00:40:16.140 --> 00:40:18.680
to make people conscious of
the fact that you're around,

00:40:18.680 --> 00:40:20.540
sponsorship is very good at it.

00:40:20.540 --> 00:40:22.370
But you need to do
your before and after.

00:40:22.370 --> 00:40:23.762
Most people will tell you--

00:40:23.762 --> 00:40:25.595
if you ask people in
Google, how many people

00:40:25.595 --> 00:40:26.780
have heard of Google?

00:40:26.780 --> 00:40:27.690
Well, Google's
probably a bad example.

00:40:27.690 --> 00:40:30.170
You're like, oh my god, the
whole world's heard of Google.

00:40:30.170 --> 00:40:31.300
Is there anybody
left in the world?

00:40:31.300 --> 00:40:32.250
There's a couple of
people [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:32.250 --> 00:40:33.833
I believe who haven't
heard of us yet,

00:40:33.833 --> 00:40:35.240
but everybody has heard.

00:40:35.240 --> 00:40:36.965
Every SME does the same thing.

00:40:36.965 --> 00:40:38.631
They say, well, they're
very well known.

00:40:38.631 --> 00:40:40.667
And it is true within
their own circle.

00:40:40.667 --> 00:40:42.500
So if it's within a
public relations circle,

00:40:42.500 --> 00:40:45.285
or within an IT circle, they
probably are very well known,

00:40:45.285 --> 00:40:48.290
but they're not very well
known to a wider world.

00:40:48.290 --> 00:40:50.176
So if you're sponsoring
within the community

00:40:50.176 --> 00:40:53.480
because you just want the
community to know who you are,

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:55.090
what you do, you're
on their doorstep,

00:40:55.090 --> 00:40:56.798
and they should really
be thinking of you

00:40:56.798 --> 00:40:59.377
in terms of maybe
future employment,

00:40:59.377 --> 00:41:01.210
and just saying to
people they're good guys,

00:41:01.210 --> 00:41:03.449
and they're out there,
they're doing great work.

00:41:03.449 --> 00:41:04.990
Then it will work
very well for that.

00:41:04.990 --> 00:41:07.630
But you need research in
advance and research afterwards.

00:41:07.630 --> 00:41:09.449
It doesn't have to
be hugely scientific.

00:41:09.449 --> 00:41:11.490
You can-- so long as you
structure the questions.

00:41:11.490 --> 00:41:12.556
You probably know
this, but so long

00:41:12.556 --> 00:41:14.610
as you structure the questions
so that they're open enough

00:41:14.610 --> 00:41:16.319
and people don't know
what the answer is.

00:41:16.319 --> 00:41:18.818
Because if you ask people, do
you think Google is wonderful,

00:41:18.818 --> 00:41:19.775
they say, yes, I do.

00:41:19.775 --> 00:41:22.234
They think Google is
awful, they'd say probably.

00:41:22.234 --> 00:41:23.900
If you say, what do
you think of Google,

00:41:23.900 --> 00:41:26.274
you'll get an honest answer
because you haven't told them

00:41:26.274 --> 00:41:27.500
what you expect.

00:41:27.500 --> 00:41:29.505
You can do it by, if
it's a community thing,

00:41:29.505 --> 00:41:31.335
you can send people out
into the community saying,

00:41:31.335 --> 00:41:33.043
have you ever heard
of this organization?

00:41:33.043 --> 00:41:34.090
Any idea of what they do?

00:41:34.090 --> 00:41:36.870
Who's in the building
down on the corner there?

00:41:36.870 --> 00:41:38.420
And you find out a
lot, but what you

00:41:38.420 --> 00:41:41.097
do is you go back and do
same research afterwards.

00:41:41.097 --> 00:41:43.180
And don't expect that
everybody will suddenly say,

00:41:43.180 --> 00:41:44.900
oh my god, we've
all heard about you.

00:41:44.900 --> 00:41:47.969
But if you get like a 5%
increase, that's good.

00:41:47.969 --> 00:41:49.510
You're moving in
the right direction.

00:41:49.510 --> 00:41:51.260
And again, it's targeted
to your audience.

00:41:51.260 --> 00:41:53.804
So the people you stop to ask
questions of, we sent a group--

00:41:53.804 --> 00:41:55.470
I'm sorry, it's very
long-winded answer.

00:41:55.470 --> 00:41:57.230
But we sent a group
out at one stage.

00:41:57.230 --> 00:41:58.970
And we were training
journalists.

00:41:58.970 --> 00:42:01.012
And I sent them out to do
interviews with people.

00:42:01.012 --> 00:42:03.470
And I said, now, be sure you
don't get all the same people.

00:42:03.470 --> 00:42:05.175
So don't stop people
who look like you.

00:42:05.175 --> 00:42:06.800
Stop people across
a mix of age groups.

00:42:06.800 --> 00:42:07.591
Stop men and women.

00:42:07.591 --> 00:42:11.097
Do everything from like
17 to 77, or something.

00:42:11.097 --> 00:42:13.760
And try and make something,
make some kind of note

00:42:13.760 --> 00:42:17.910
about middle-aged, senior
person, younger person,

00:42:17.910 --> 00:42:19.640
so when you come
back, you can say,

00:42:19.640 --> 00:42:21.440
I interviewed-- because
it was for radio.

00:42:21.440 --> 00:42:23.180
So I interviewed 10 people.

00:42:23.180 --> 00:42:26.060
Four of them would've under 25,
and the others were over 55.

00:42:26.060 --> 00:42:28.226
And the guys actually were
Ital-- they were Italian.

00:42:28.226 --> 00:42:29.630
Any Italians in the room?

00:42:29.630 --> 00:42:32.040
They have a whole 'nother
way of doing things.

00:42:32.040 --> 00:42:34.830
So then he went up and he
said, hello, I'm John Marco.

00:42:34.830 --> 00:42:36.714
So please, you'll tell
me how old are you?

00:42:36.714 --> 00:42:38.140
And they said,
I'm 36 and a half.

00:42:38.140 --> 00:42:38.988
I'm 42.

00:42:38.988 --> 00:42:39.412
I couldn't believe it.

00:42:39.412 --> 00:42:41.453
If an Orange person did
it, they would pick me up

00:42:41.453 --> 00:42:42.762
off the ground.

00:42:42.762 --> 00:42:44.983
But it's the audience
you're trying to reach.

00:42:44.983 --> 00:42:47.750
So if you target the age
group as well carefully,

00:42:47.750 --> 00:42:50.132
but that also means watching
who you send out to do it.

00:42:50.132 --> 00:42:52.090
Send out a young person
to target older people,

00:42:52.090 --> 00:42:53.360
they won't do it as well.

00:42:53.360 --> 00:42:56.300
Send out an older person that's
in same age group stopping him,

00:42:56.300 --> 00:42:57.962
you'll get more honest answers.

00:42:57.962 --> 00:43:00.211
AUDIENCE: I was wondering,
