in Orange who studies PR.

00:43:19.700 --> 00:43:21.255
So, we're expecting
more colleges

00:43:21.255 --> 00:43:22.480
to-- it's an academic text.

00:43:22.480 --> 00:43:23.580
It's an [INAUDIBLE].

00:43:23.580 --> 00:43:24.462
It's a doorstop.

00:43:24.462 --> 00:43:26.690
It's about 600
pages or something.

00:43:26.690 --> 00:43:28.860
I actually thought that
I'd be revising that book

00:43:28.860 --> 00:43:30.400
but not doing
anything else with PR.

00:43:30.400 --> 00:43:34.020
And I had met with Mercier
Press, who published the book.

00:43:34.020 --> 00:43:37.232
And I actually met with
them about a client's book.

00:43:37.232 --> 00:43:38.899
And they had said--I
sent them the page.

00:43:38.899 --> 00:43:40.606
And they came back
and said, actually, we

00:43:40.606 --> 00:43:41.670
wouldn't be interested.

00:43:41.670 --> 00:43:44.320
We'll meet you, and we would
be interested in publishing

00:43:44.320 --> 00:43:45.320
the book for the client.

00:43:45.320 --> 00:43:46.130
So I said, that's fine.

00:43:46.130 --> 00:43:47.850
I really appreciate you
having a look at it.

00:43:47.850 --> 00:43:49.433
Where else should
we go with the book?

00:43:49.433 --> 00:43:50.582
Who else should publish it?

00:43:50.582 --> 00:43:51.530
And at the end of
the conversation,

00:43:51.530 --> 00:43:52.850
she says, you're
never going to write

00:43:52.850 --> 00:43:55.155
another book on public
relations yourself, did you?

00:43:55.155 --> 00:43:57.857
And I said, well, to
answer your question, no,

00:43:57.857 --> 00:43:59.440
because I've kind
of covered everybody

00:43:59.440 --> 00:44:00.439
who studies the subject.

00:44:00.439 --> 00:44:02.750
And she said, well,
why what about SMEs?

00:44:02.750 --> 00:44:03.597
Oh, yeah.

00:44:03.597 --> 00:44:04.180
I [INAUDIBLE].

00:44:04.180 --> 00:44:04.910
I have no sense.

00:44:04.910 --> 00:44:06.910
They say yes to all the
things that interest me.

00:44:06.910 --> 00:44:07.800
And then give out
[INAUDIBLE] and just

00:44:07.800 --> 00:44:09.970
say, why did I decide to
d-- who scheduled this?

00:44:09.970 --> 00:44:10.690
Me.

00:44:10.690 --> 00:44:12.356
But I actually
thought, great idea.

00:44:12.356 --> 00:44:14.495
And it was completely
different because essentially

00:44:14.495 --> 00:44:17.890
what I'll do is-- and I know
the things that SMEs use,

00:44:17.890 --> 00:44:19.940
but it gave me an opportunity
to go out and look

00:44:19.940 --> 00:44:21.750
for companies in that sector.

00:44:21.750 --> 00:44:23.694
Because we all look at
the larger companies,

00:44:23.694 --> 00:44:25.110
so let's look at
smaller companies

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:27.076
and see how they're
using it well,

00:44:27.076 --> 00:44:29.000
and how we could use
them as case studies.

00:44:29.000 --> 00:44:30.943
So the audience
almost found itself

00:44:30.943 --> 00:44:33.026
